We update forecasts for FY25 reporting. Primary changes are: i) increase forward sales growth in Kmart noting strong trading update; ii) marginal increases in EBIT margins for Bunnings and Kmart as we assume additional operating leverage (noting strong 2H25 sales) to offset cost inflation; iii) additional losses in Lithium in FY26 broadly consistent with FY25 ( \(\sim \Delta \Phi 60m\) loss). We also adjust interest cost assumptions. SOTP valuation of A\$76.1 - We apply an EV/EBIT multiple approach to WES's reporting divisions, in which the multiple applied to each division is derived from the mid cycle multiple of a subset of listed comps.

WES is trading at 2- SD above mean on both an absolute and index- relative basis, and, given limited earnings growth seen for FY25e, valuation is expensive, in our opinion. We forecast a muted growth outlook for FY25 earnings, driven by a combination of i) weakness in construction activity, ii) rebased WesCEF earnings, and iii) a cautious consumer. Upside risks include utilisation of balance sheet to execute on M&A, a more resilient- than- anticipated consumer and/or property market.

Bunnings LFL of \(4 - 5\%\) FY26e and beyond) driven by a more resilient consumer and housing market. WesCEF ex. lithium earnings supported by a more- favorable- than- expected commodity complex. Lithium pricing ahead of our estimates.

Bunnings delivers FY26e \(3.5\%\) LFL sales growth as the rebuild to normalized growth extends into FY27e. WesCEF rebased as key commodity prices normalise. Kmart continues to do well given a consumer shift to value. Lithium production aligns with management guidance. Additional capital management.
A more protracted decline in domestic property and a greater slowdown than forecast in discretionary spending results in a greater contraction in FY28 LFL growth. Lithium pricing below our estimates.

Overweight (O). The stock's total return is expected to exceed the average total return of the analyst's industry (or industry team's) coverage universe, on a risk-adjusted basis, over the next 12- 18 months.

Equal-weight (E). The stock's total return is expected to be in line with the average total return of the analyst's industry (or industry team's) coverage universe, on a risk-adjusted basis, over the next 12- 18 months.

Not-Rated (NR). Currently the analyst does not have adequate conviction about the stock's total return relative to the average total return of the analyst's industry (or industry team's) coverage universe, on a risk-adjusted basis, over the next 12- 18 months.

Underweight (U). The stock's total return is expected to be below the average total return of the analyst's industry (or industry team's) coverage universe, on a risk-adjusted basis, over the next 12- 18 months.
